<date id="FFBD1006FFF3FF9AFB80FBAAFB075378" box="[1073,1226,1026,1053]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" value="2021-04-24">24 April 2021</date>
; P. J. C. Camancho. Host: 
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF3FF9AFEB3FB8DFCED535A" authority="(F. O. Pickard-Cambridge)" baseAuthorityName="F. O. Pickard-Cambridge" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[258,800,1060,1087]" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Phoneutria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boliviensis">
<emphasis id="B977EAD4FFF3FF9AFEB3FB8DFE3E535B" box="[258,499,1060,1086]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Phoneutria boliviensis</emphasis>
(F. O. Pickard-Cambridge)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF3FF9AFC9FFB8DFC55535A" box="[814,920,1060,1087]" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ctenidae</taxonomicName>
), adult or subadult female. The wasp pulled the paralyzed armed spider over and through low grass, dorsal side upward, grasping the base of its right pedipalp with her mandibles (
<bibRefCitation id="EF924B37FFF3FF9AFE16FBCEFDA053E4" author="Camancho PJC" box="[423,621,1127,1153]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref21577" refString="Camancho PJC. 2021 a. Hymenoptera&gt; Pompilidae (??) - Avispon. Available at https: // www. facebook. com / 2701 Pedro JoseCardonaCamacho / photos / 366387848169534. (Last accessed 5 December 2021)." type="url" year="2021">Camancho 2021a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF924B37FFF3FF9AFDC9FBCEFD7053E4" author="Camancho PJC" box="[632,701,1127,1153]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref21619" refString="Camancho PJC. 2021 b. Hymenoptera&gt; Pompilidae (??) - Avispon. Available at https: // www. facebook. com / 2701 Pedro JoseCardonaCamacho / photos / 366387808169538. (Last accessed 5 December 2021)." type="url" year="2021">2021b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF924B37FFF3FF9AFD79FBCEFCC353E4" author="Camancho PJC" box="[712,782,1127,1153]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref21661" refString="Camancho PJC. 2021 c. Hymenoptera&gt; Pompilidae (??) - Avispon. Available at https: // www. facebook. com / 2701 Pedro JoseCardonaCamacho / photos / 366387771502875. (Last accessed 5 December 2021)." type="url" year="2021">2021c</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBC36C6FFF3FF9AFEB1FB20FDBF524C" blockId="6.[191,1441,990,1322]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<collectingCountry id="F3147656FFF3FF9AFEB1FB20FE5E53C6" box="[256,403,1161,1187]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">COLOMBIA</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion id="49C7F824FFF3FF9AFE2CFB20FD5853C6" box="[413,661,1161,1187]" country="Colombia" name="Casanare" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Casanare Department</collectingRegion>
, Yopal; 
<date id="FFBD1006FFF3FF9AFD5AFB20FC0D53C6" box="[747,960,1161,1187]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" value="2020-11-22">22 November 2020</date>
; 
<collectionCode id="ED12AE03FFF3FF9AFC7AFB20FC1053C6" box="[971,989,1161,1187]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">T</collectionCode>
. C. Bedoya. Host: 
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF3FF9AFB16FB20FAFD53C6" authorityName="Bertkau" authorityYear="1880" box="[1191,1328,1161,1187]" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" genus="Ancylometes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B977EAD4FFF3FF9AFB16FB20FAFD53C6" box="[1191,1328,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Ancylometes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
? 
<emphasis id="B977EAD4FFF3FF9AFAF0FB20FF1753A1" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">bogotensis</emphasis>
(Keyserling) (
<taxonomicName id="4C034D45FFF3FF9AFEC8FB03FE2E53A0" box="[377,483,1194,1221]" class="Arachnida" family="Ctenidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ctenidae</taxonomicName>
), adult or subadult female. Two photographs show the wasp straddling the wandering spider on the ground, dorsal side upward, while stinging it between the bases of its 1 
<superScript id="7C769B8EFFF3FF9AFBD4FB65FBBD53BF" attach="left" box="[1125,1136,1228,1242]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">st</superScript>
and 2 
<superScript id="7C769B8EFFF3FF9AFB02FB65FB0953BF" attach="left" box="[1203,1220,1228,1242]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">nd</superScript>
left legs. The 3 
<superScript id="7C769B8EFFF3FF9AFAD9FB65FABB53BF" attach="right" box="[1384,1398,1228,1242]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">rd</superScript>
–6 
<superScript id="7C769B8EFFF3FF9AFA23FB65FA6D53BF" attach="none" box="[1426,1440,1228,1242]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">th</superScript>
photographs show the wasp examining the paralyzed wandering spider with her antennae as it laid, dorsal side upward, on the ground (
<bibRefCitation id="EF924B37FFF3FF9AFE61FAA6FDAB524C" author="Bedoya TC" box="[464,614,1295,1321]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref21256" refString="Bedoya TC. 2020. Pepsis caridei. Available at https: // www. inaturalist. org / observations / 65771570. (Last accessed 5 December 2021)." type="url" year="2020">Bedoya 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
